Root cause: A Groovy Script step in the iFlow attempted to parse the message body as strict JSON using Gson/JsonReader. The runtime payload was not valid JSON at the first character (likely empty, an HTML/text error page from a backend call, or a payload containing a BOM), causing the parser to throw 'Use JsonReader.setLenient(true) to accept malformed JSON at line 1 column 1 path $' and resulting in a 500 BACKEND_ERROR.
Suggested fix: Implement a content-type and payload guard before JSON parsing so the script only parses when Content-Type is application/json and the body is non-empty valid JSON; otherwise, branch/skip parsing and handle non-JSON or empty responses gracefully. Normalize inputs by stripping UTF-8 BOM if present. For upstream HTTP calls, set/verify Accept: application/json and check HTTP status and response Content-Type before passing the body to the JSON parser; handle non-2xx and non-JSON responses explicitly to avoid feeding them into the JSON parser. If lenient parsing is acceptable for this flow, enable JsonReader.setLenient(true) as a fallback, but prefer strict mode with guards. Also validate backend endpoint/credentials to prevent HTML error responses.
